b'' b'this file and other text and image files from jpl missions are' b'available from the jpl info public access computer site,' b'reachable by internet via anonymous ftp to pubinfo.jpl.nasa.gov' b'(128.149.6.2); or by dialup modem to up to' b'9600 bits per second, parameters n-8-1.' b'-----------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'our solar system at a glance' b'' b'information summary' b'pms 010-a (jpl)' b'june b'' b'jpl b'' b'nasa' b'national aeronautics and space administration' b'' b'jet propulsion laboratory' b'california institue of technology' b'pasadena, california' b'' b'' b'for a printed copy of this publication contact the public mail' b'office at the nasa center in your geographic region.' b'' b'' b'' b'introduction' b'' b'from our small world we have gazed upon the cosmic ocean for' b'untold thousands of years. ancient astronomers observed points of' b'light that appeared to move among the stars. they called these' b'objects planets, meaning wanderers, and named them after roman' b'deities jupiter, king of the gods; mars, the god of war;' b'mercury, messenger of the gods; venus, the god of love and' b'beauty, and saturn, father of jupiter and god of agriculture. the' b'stargazers also observed comets with sparkling tails, and meteors' b'or shooting stars apparently falling from the sky.' b'' b'science flourished during the european renaissance.' b'fundamental physical laws governing planetary motion were' b'discovered, and the orbits of the planets around the sun were' b'calculated. in the 17th century, astronomers pointed a new device' b'called the telescope at the heavens and made startling' b'discoveries.' b'' b'but the years since have amounted to a golden age of' b'solar system exploration. advancements in rocketry after world' b"war ii enabled our machines to break the grip of earth's gravity" b'and travel to the moon and to other planets.' b'' b'the united states has sent automated spacecraft, then' b'human-crewed expeditions, to explore the moon. our automated' b'machines have orbited and landed on venus and mars; explored the' b"sun's environment; observed comets, and made close-range surveys" b'while flying past mercury, jupiter, saturn, uranus and neptune.' b'' b'these travelers brought a quantum leap in our knowledge and' b'understanding of the solar system. through the electronic sight' b'and other "senses" of our automated spacecraft, color and' b'complexion have been given to worlds that for centuries appeared' b'to earth-bound eyes as fuzzy disks or indistinct points of light.' b'and dozens of previously unknown objects have been discovered.' b'' b'future historians will likely view these pioneering flights' b'through the solar system as some of the most remarkable' b'achievements of the 20th century.' b'' b'' b'automated spacecraft' b'' b"the national aeronautics and space administration's (nasa's)" b'automated spacecraft for solar system exploration come in many' b'shapes and sizes. while they are designed to fulfill separate and' b'specific mission objectives, the craft share much in common.' b'' b'each spacecraft consists of various scientific instruments' b'selected for a particular mission, supported by basic subsystems' b'for electrical power, trajectory and orientation control, as well' b'as for processing data and communicating with earth.' b'' b'electrical power is required to operate the spacecraft' b'instruments and systems. nasa uses both solar energy from arrays' b'of photovoltaic cells and small nuclear generators to power its' b'solar system missions. rechargeable batteries are employed for' b'backup and supplemental power.' b'' b'imagine that a spacecraft has successfully journeyed' b'millions of miles through space to fly but one time near a' b'planet, only to have its cameras and other sensing instruments' b'pointed the wrong way as it speeds past the target! to help' b'prevent such a mishap, a subsystem of small thrusters is used to' b'control spacecraft.' b'' b'the thrusters are linked with devices that maintain a' b"constant gaze at selected stars. just as earth's early seafarers" b'used the stars to navigate the oceans, spacecraft use stars to' b'maintain their bearings in space. with the subsystem locked onto' b'fixed points of reference, flight controllers can keep a' b"spacecraft's scientific instruments pointed at the target body" b"and the craft's communications antennas pointed toward earth. the" b'thrusters can also be used to fine-tune the flight path and speed' b'of the spacecraft to ensure that a target body is encountered at' b'the planned distance and on the proper trajectory.' b'' b'between and nasa spacecraft were dispatched to' b'study the moon and the solar environment; they also scanned the' b'inner planets other than earth mercury, venus and mars. these' b'three worlds, and our own, are known as the terrestrial planets' b'because they share a solid-rock composition.' b'' b'for the early planetary reconnaissance missions, nasa' b'employed a highly successful series of spacecraft called the' b'mariners. their flights helped shape the planning of later' b'missions. between and seven mariner missions conducted' b'the first surveys of our planetary neighbors in space.' b'' b'all of the mariners used solar panels as their primary power' b'source. the first and the final versions of the spacecraft had' b'two wings covered with photovoltaic cells. other mariners were' b'equipped with four solar panels extending from their octagonal' b'bodies.' b'' b'although the mariners ranged from the mariner venus' b'spacecraft, weighing in at kilograms pounds), to the' b'mariner mars orbiter, weighing in at kilograms b'pounds), their basic design remained quite similar throughout the' b'program. the mariner venus spacecraft, for example, had' b'originally been a backup for the mariner mars flyby. the' b'mariner spacecraft sent to venus and mercury used components' b'left over from the mariner mars orbiter program.' b'' b'in nasa launched pioneer a jupiter spacecraft.' b'interest was shifting to four of the outer planets jupiter,' b'saturn, uranus and neptune giant balls of dense gas quite' b'different from the terrestrial worlds we had already surveyed.' b'' b'four nasa spacecraft in all two pioneers and two voyagers' b'-- were sent in the 1970s to tour the outer regions of our solar' b'system. because of the distances involved, these travelers took' b'anywhere from months to years to reach their destinations.' b'barring faster spacecraft, they will eventually become the first' b"human artifacts to journey to distant stars. because the sun's" b'light becomes so faint in the outer solar system, these travelers' b'do not use solar power but instead operate on electricity' b'generated by heat from the decay of radioisotopes.' b'' b'nasa also developed highly specialized spacecraft to revisit' b'our neighbors mars and venus in the middle and late 1970s. twin' b'viking landers were equipped to serve as seismic and weather' b'stations and as biology laboratories. two advanced orbiters b'descendants of the mariner craft carried the viking landers' b'from earth and then studied martian features from above.' b'' b'two drum-shaped pioneer spacecraft visited venus in b'the pioneer venus orbiter was equipped with a radar instrument' b'that allowed it to "see" through the planet\'s dense cloud cover' b'to study surface features. the pioneer venus multiprobe carried' b'four probes that were dropped through the clouds. the probes and' b'the main body all of which contained scientific instruments b"radioed information about the planet's atmosphere during their" b'descent toward the surface.' b'' b'a new generation of automated spacecraft including' b'magellan, galileo, ulysses, mars observer, the comet' b'rendezvous/asteroid flyby (craf) and cassini is being' b'developed and sent out into the solar system to make detailed' b'examinations that will increase our understanding of our' b'neighborhood and our own planet.' b'' b'' b'the sun' b'' b'a discussion of the objects in the solar system must start' b'with the sun. the sun dwarfs the other bodies, representing' b'approximately percent of all the mass in the solar system;' b'all of the planets, moons, asteroids, comets, dust and gas add up' b'to only about percent. this percent represents the' b"material left over from the sun's formation. one hundred and nine" b"earths would be required to fit across the sun's disk, and its" b'interior could hold over million earths.' b'' b'as a star, the sun generates energy through the process of' b"fusion. the temperature at the sun's core is million degrees" b'celsius million degrees fahrenheit), and the pressure there' b"is billion times earth's air pressure at sea level. the sun's" b'surface temperature of degrees celsius degrees' b'fahrenheit) seems almost chilly compared to its core-temperature.' b'at the solar core, hydrogen can fuse into helium, producing' b'energy. the sun also produces a strong magnetic field and streams' b'of charged particles, both extending far beyond the planets.' b'' b'the sun appears to have been active for billion years' b'and has enough fuel to go on for another five billion years or' b'so. at the end of its life, the sun will start to fuse helium' b'into heavier elements and begin to swell up, ultimately growing' b'so large that it will swallow earth. after a billion years as a' b'"red giant," it will suddenly collapse into a "white dwarf" b'the final end product of a star like ours. it may take a trillion' b'years to cool off completely.' b'' b"many spacecraft have explored the sun's environment, but" b'none have gotten any closer to its surface than approximately' b'two-thirds of the distance from earth to the sun. pioneers b'the pioneer venus orbiter, voyagers and and other spacecraft' b'have all sampled the solar environment. the ulysses spacecraft,' b'launched on october is a joint solar mission of nasa and' b"the european space agency. after using jupiter's gravity to" b"change its trajectory, ulysses will fly over the sun's polar" b'regions during and and will perform a wide range of' b'studies using nine onboard scientific instruments.' b'' b'we are fortunate that the sun is exactly the way it is. if' b'it were different in almost any way, life would almost certainly' b'never have developed on earth.' b'' b'' b'mercury' b'' b'obtaining the first close-up views of mercury was the' b'primary objective of the mariner spacecraft, launched on' b'november from kennedy space center in florida. after a' b'journey of nearly five months, which included a flyby of venus,' b'the spacecraft passed within kilometers miles) of the' b"solar system's innermost planet on march b'' b'until mariner little was known about mercury. even the' b'best telescopic views from earth showed mercury as an indistinct' b'object lacking any surface detail. the planet is so close to the' b'sun that it is usually lost in solar glare. when the planet is' b"visible on earth's horizon just after sunset or before dawn, it" b'is obscured by the haze and dust in our atmosphere. only radar' b"telescopes gave any hint of mercury's surface conditions prior to" b'the voyage of mariner b'' b'the photographs mariner radioed back to earth revealed an' b'ancient, heavily cratered surface, closely resembling our own' b'moon. the pictures also showed huge cliffs crisscrossing the' b"planet. these apparently were created when mercury's interior" b"cooled and shrank, buckling the planet's crust. the cliffs are as" b'high as kilometers miles) and as long as kilometers b'miles).' b'' b'instruments on mariner discovered that mercury has a weak' b'magnetic field and a trace of atmosphere a trillionth the' b"density of earth's atmosphere and composed chiefly of argon, neon" b"and helium. when the planet's orbit takes it closest to the sun," b'surface temperatures range from degrees celsius degrees' b"fahrenheit) on mercury's sunlit side to degrees celsius" b'(-298 degrees fahrenheit) on the dark side. this range in surface' b'temperature degrees celsius degrees fahrenheit) b'is the largest for a single body in the solar system. mercury' b'literally bakes and freezes at the same time.' b'' b'days and nights are long on mercury. the combination of a' b'slow rotation relative to the stars earth days) and a rapid' b'revolution around the sun earth days) means that one mercury' b'solar day takes earth days or two mercury years the time' b'it takes the innermost planet to complete two orbits around the' b'sun!' b'' b'mercury appears to have a crust of light silicate rock like' b'that of earth. scientists believe mercury has a heavy iron-rich' b'core making up slightly less than half of its volume. that would' b"make mercury's core larger, proportionally, than the moon's core" b'or those of any of the planets.' b'' b'after the initial mercury encounter, mariner made two' b'additional flybys on september and march b'before control gas used to orient the spacecraft was exhausted' b'and the mission was concluded. each flyby took place at the same' b'local mercury time when the identical half of the planet was' b'illuminated; as a result, we still have not seen one-half of the' b"planet's surface." b'' b'' b'venus' b'' b'veiled by dense cloud cover, venus our nearest planetary' b'neighbor was the first planet to be explored. the mariner b'spacecraft, launched on august was the first of more' b'than a dozen successful american and soviet missions to study the' b'mysterious planet. as spacecraft flew by or orbited venus,' b"plunged into the atmosphere or gently landed on venus' surface," b'romantic myths and speculations about our neighbor were laid to' b'rest.' b'' b'on december mariner passed within b'kilometers miles) of venus and became the first' b'spacecraft to scan another planet; onboard instruments measured' b'venus for minutes. mariner launched in june flew much' b'closer to the planet. passing within kilometers b"miles) of venus on the second american flyby, mariner 5's" b"instruments measured the planet's magnetic field, ionosphere," b'radiation belts and temperatures. on its way to mercury, mariner' b'10 flew by venus and transmitted ultraviolet pictures to earth' b'showing cloud circulation patterns in the venusian atmosphere.' b'' b'in the spring and summer of two spacecraft were' b'launched to further unravel the mysteries of venus. on december b'of the same year, the pioneer venus orbiter became the first' b'spacecraft placed in orbit around the planet.' b'' b'five days later, the five separate components making up the' b'second spacecraft the pioneer venus multiprobe entered the' b'venusian atmosphere at different locations above the planet. the' b'four small, independent probes and the main body radioed' b'atmospheric data back to earth during their descent toward the' b'surface. although designed to examine the atmosphere, one of the' b'probes survived its impact with the surface and continued to' b'transmit data for another hour.' b'' b'venus resembles earth in size, physical composition and' b'density more closely than any other known planet. however,' b'spacecraft have discovered significant differences as well. for' b"example, venus' rotation (west to east) is retrograde (backward)" b'compared to the east-to-west spin of earth and most of the other' b'planets.' b'' b"approximately percent of venus' atmosphere times as" b"dense as earth's) is carbon dioxide. the principal constituent of" b"earth's atmosphere is nitrogen. venus' atmosphere acts like a" b'greenhouse, permitting solar radiation to reach the surface but' b'trapping the heat that would ordinarily be radiated back into' b"space. as a result, the planet's average surface temperature is" b'482 degrees celsius degrees fahrenheit), hot enough to melt' b'lead.' b'' b'a radio altimeter on the pioneer venus orbiter provided the' b"first means of seeing through the planet's dense cloud cover and" b'determining surface features over almost the entire planet.' b"nasa's magellan spacecraft, launched on may has been in" b'orbit around venus since august the spacecraft uses' b'radar-mapping techniques to provide ultrahigh-resolution images' b'of the surface.' b'' b'magellan has revealed a landscape dominated by volcanic' b'features, faults and impact craters. huge areas of the surface' b'show evidence of multiple periods of lava flooding with flows' b'lying on top of previous ones. an elevated region named ishtar' b'terra is a lava-filled basin as large as the united states. at' b'one end of this plateau sits maxwell montes, a mountain the size' b"of mount everest. scarring the mountain's flank is a" b'100-kilometer (62-mile) wide, 2.5-kilometer (1.5-mile) deep' b'impact crater named cleopatra. (almost all features on venus are' b'named for women; maxwell montes, alpha regio and beta regio are' b'the exceptions.) craters survive on venus for perhaps million' b'years because there is no water and very little wind erosion.' b'' b'extensive fault-line networks cover the planet, probably the' b'result of the same crustal flexing that produces plate tectonics' b'on earth. but on venus the surface temperature is sufficient to' b'weaken the rock, which cracks just about everywhere, preventing' b'the formation of major plates and large earthquake faults like' b'the san andreas fault in california.' b'' b"venus' predominant weather pattern is a high-altitude," b'high-speed circulation of clouds that contain sulfuric acid. at' b'speeds reaching as high as kilometers miles) per hour,' b'the clouds circle the planet in only four earth days. the' b"circulation is in the same direction west to east as venus'" b"slow rotation of earth days, whereas earth's winds blow in" b'both directions west to east and east to west in six' b"alternating bands. venus' atmosphere serves as a simplified" b'laboratory for the study of our weather.' b'' b'' b'earth' b'' b"as viewed from space, our world's distinguishing" b'characteristics are its blue waters, brown and green land masses' b'and white clouds. we are enveloped by an ocean of air consisting' b'of percent nitrogen, percent oxygen and percent other' b'constituents. the only planet in the solar system known to harbor' b'life, earth orbits the sun at an average distance of million' b'kilometers million miles). earth is the third planet from the' b'sun and the fifth largest in the solar system, with a diameter' b'just a few hundred kilometers larger than that of venus.' b'' b"our planet's rapid spin and molten nickel-iron core give" b'rise to an extensive magnetic field, which, along with the' b'atmosphere, shields us from nearly all of the harmful radiation' b"coming from the sun and other stars. earth's atmosphere protects" b'us from meteors as well, most of which burn up before they can' b'strike the surface. active geological processes have left no' b'evidence of the pelting earth almost certainly received soon' b'after it formed about billion years ago. along with the' b'other newly formed planets, it was showered by space debris in' b'the early days of the solar system.' b'' b'from our journeys into space, we have learned much about our' b'home planet. the first american satellite explorer was' b'launched from cape canaveral in florida on january and' b'discovered an intense radiation zone, now called the van allen' b'radiation belts, surrounding earth.' b'' b'since then, other research satellites have revealed that our' b"planet's magnetic field is distorted into a tear-drop shape by" b'the solar wind the stream of charged particles continuously' b"ejected from the sun. we've learned that the magnetic field does" b'not fade off into space but has definite boundaries. and we now' b'know that our wispy upper atmosphere, once believed calm and' b'uneventful, seethes with activity swelling by day and' b'contracting by night. affected by changes in solar activity, the' b'upper atmosphere contributes to weather and climate on earth.' b'' b"besides affecting earth's weather, solar activity gives rise" b'to a dramatic visual phenomenon in our atmosphere. when charged' b"particles from the solar wind become trapped in earth's magnetic" b"field, they collide with air molecules above our planet's" b'magnetic poles. these air molecules then begin to glow and are' b'known as the auroras or the northern and southern lights.' b'' b'satellites about kilometers miles) out in' b'space play a major role in daily local weather forecasting. these' b'watchful electronic eyes warn us of dangerous storms. continuous' b'global monitoring provides a vast amount of useful data and' b"contributes to a better understanding of earth's complex weather" b'systems.' b'' b'from their unique vantage points, satellites can survey' b"earth's oceans, land use and resources, and monitor the planet's" b'health. these eyes in space have saved countless lives, provided' b'tremendous conveniences and shown us that we may be altering our' b'planet in dangerous ways.' b'' b'' b'the moon' b'' b"the moon is earth's single natural satellite. the first" b'human footsteps on an alien world were made by american' b'astronauts on the dusty surface of our airless, lifeless' b'companion. in preparation for the human-crewed apollo' b'expeditions, nasa dispatched the automated ranger, surveyor and' b'lunar orbiter spacecraft to study the moon between and b'' b"nasa's apollo program left a large legacy of lunar materials" b'and data. six two-astronaut crews landed on and explored the' b'lunar surface between and carrying back a collection' b'of rocks and soil weighing a total of kilograms pounds)' b'and consisting of more than separate samples.' b'' b'from this material and other studies, scientists have' b'constructed a history of the moon that includes its infancy.' b'rocks collected from the lunar highlands date to about b"billion years old. the first few million years of the moon's" b'existence were so violent that few traces of this period remain.' b'as a molten outer layer gradually cooled and solidified into' b'different kinds of rock, the moon was bombarded by huge asteroids' b'and smaller objects. some of the asteroids were as large as rhode' b'island or delaware, and their collisions with the moon created' b'basins hundreds of kilometers across.' b'' b'this catastrophic bombardment tapered off approximately four' b'billion years ago, leaving the lunar highlands covered with huge,' b'overlapping craters and a deep layer of shattered and broken' b'rock. heat produced by the decay of radioactive elements began to' b'melt the interior of the moon at depths of about kilometers' b'(125 miles) below the surface. then, for the next million' b'years from about to billion years ago lava rose' b'from inside the moon. the lava gradually spread out over the' b'surface, flooding the large impact basins to form the dark areas' b'that galileo galilei, an astronomer of the italian renaissance,' b'called maria, meaning seas.' b'' b'as far as we can tell, there has been no significant' b'volcanic activity on the moon for more than three billion years.' b'since then, the lunar surface has been altered only by' b'micrometeorites, by the atomic particles from the sun and stars,' b'by the rare impacts of large meteorites and by spacecraft and' b'astronauts. if our astronauts had landed on the moon a billion' b'years ago, they would have seen a landscape very similar to the' b'one today. thousands of years from now, the footsteps left by the' b'apollo crews will remain sharp and clear.' b'' b'the origin of the moon is still a mystery. four theories' b'attempt an explanation: the moon formed near earth as a separate' b'body; it was torn from earth; it formed somewhere else and was' b"captured by our planet's gravity, or it was the result of a" b'collision between earth and an asteroid about the size of mars.' b'the last theory has some good support but is far from certain.' b'' b'' b'mars' b'' b'of all the planets, mars has long been considered the solar' b"system's prime candidate for harboring extraterrestrial life." b'astronomers studying the red planet through telescopes saw what' b'appeared to be straight lines crisscrossing its surface. these' b'observations later determined to be optical illusions led' b'to the popular notion that intelligent beings had constructed a' b'system of irrigation canals on the planet. in when orson' b'welles broadcast a radio drama based on the science fiction' b'classic war of the worlds by h.g. wells, enough people believed' b'in the tale of invading martians to cause a near panic.' b'' b'another reason for scientists to expect life on mars had to' b"do with the apparent seasonal color changes on the planet's" b'surface. this phenomenon led to speculation that conditions might' b'support a bloom of martian vegetation during the warmer months' b'and cause plant life to become dormant during colder periods.' b'' b'so far, six american missions to mars have been carried out.' b'four mariner spacecraft three flying by the planet and one' b'placed into martian orbit surveyed the planet extensively' b'before the viking orbiters and landers arrived.' b'' b'mariner launched in late flew past mars on july b'1965, coming within kilometers miles) of the' b'surface. transmitting to earth close-up pictures of the' b'planet, the spacecraft found many craters and naturally occurring' b'channels but no evidence of artificial canals or flowing water.' b'mariners and followed with their flybys during the summer of' b'1969 and returned pictures. mariners and showed a' b'diversity of surface conditions as well as a thin, cold, dry' b'atmosphere of carbon dioxide.' b'' b'on may the mariner orbiter was launched on a' b'mission to make a year-long study of the martian surface. the' b'spacecraft arrived five and a half months after lift-off, only to' b'find mars in the midst of a planet-wide dust storm that made' b'surface photography impossible for several weeks. but after the' b'storm cleared, mariner began returning the first of b'pictures; these revealed previously unknown martian features,' b'including evidence that large amounts of water once flowed across' b'the surface, etching river valleys and flood plains.' b'' b'in august and september the viking and spacecraft' b'-- each consisting of an orbiter and a lander lifted off from' b'kennedy space center. the mission was designed to answer several' b'questions about the red planet, including, is there life there?' b'nobody expected the spacecraft to spot martian cities, but it was' b'hoped that the biology experiments on the viking landers would at' b'least find evidence of primitive life past or present.' b'' b'viking lander became the first spacecraft to successfully' b'touch down on another planet when it landed on july b'while the united states was celebrating its bicentennial. photos' b'sent back from the chryse planitia ("plains of gold") showed a' b'bleak, rusty-red landscape. panoramic images returned by the' b'lander revealed a rolling plain, littered with rocks and marked' b'by rippled sand dunes. fine red dust from the martian soil gives' b'the sky a salmon hue. when viking lander touched down on utopia' b'planitia on september it viewed a more rolling landscape' b'than the one seen by its predecessor one without visible' b'dunes.' b'' b'the results sent back by the laboratory on each viking' b'lander were inconclusive. small samples of the red martian soil' b'were tested in three different experiments designed to detect' b'biological processes. while some of the test results seemed to' b'indicate biological activity, later analysis confirmed that this' b"activity was inorganic in nature and related to the planet's soil" b'chemistry. is there life on mars? no one knows for sure, but the' b'viking mission found no evidence that organic molecules exist' b'there.' b'' b'the viking landers became weather stations, recording wind' b'velocity and direction as well as atmospheric temperature and' b'pressure. few weather changes were observed. the highest' b'temperature recorded by either craft was degrees celsius b'degrees fahrenheit) at the viking lander site in midsummer.' b'' b'the lowest temperature, degrees celsius degrees' b'fahrenheit), was recorded at the more northerly viking lander b'site during winter. near-hurricane wind speeds were measured at' b'the two martian weather stations during global dust storms, but' b'because the atmosphere is so thin, wind force is minimal. viking' b'lander photographed light patches of frost probably' b'water-ice during its second winter on the planet.' b'' b'the martian atmosphere, like that of venus, is primarily' b'carbon dioxide. nitrogen and oxygen are present only in small' b'percentages. martian air contains only about as much' b'water as our air, but even this small amount can condense out,' b'forming clouds that ride high in the atmosphere or swirl around' b'the slopes of towering volcanoes. local patches of early morning' b'fog can form in valleys.' b'' b'there is evidence that in the past a denser martian' b'atmosphere may have allowed water to flow on the planet. physical' b'features closely resembling shorelines, gorges, riverbeds and' b'islands suggest that great rivers once marked the planet.' b'' b'mars has two moons, phobos and deimos. they are small and' b'irregularly shaped and possess ancient, cratered surfaces. it is' b'possible the moons were originally asteroids that ventured too' b'close to mars and were captured by its gravity.' b'' b'the viking orbiters and landers exceeded by large margins' b'their design lifetimes of and days, respectively. the' b'first to fail was viking orbiter which stopped operating on' b'july when a leak depleted its attitude-control gas.' b'viking lander operated until april when it was shut' b'down because of battery degeneration. viking orbiter quit on' b'august when the last of its attitude-control gas was' b'used up. viking lander ceased functioning on november b'' b'despite the inconclusive results of the viking biology' b'experiments, we know more about mars than any other planet except' b"earth. nasa's mars observer spacecraft, to be launched in" b'september will expand our knowledge of the martian' b'environment and lead to human exploration of the red planet.' b'' b'' b'asteroids' b'' b'the solar system has a large number of rocky and metallic' b'objects that are in orbit around the sun but are too small to be' b'considered full-fledged planets. these objects are known as' b'asteroids or minor planets. most, but not all, are found in a' b'band or belt between the orbits of mars and jupiter. some have' b"orbits that cross earth's path, and there is evidence that earth" b'has been hit by asteroids in the past. one of the least eroded,' b'best preserved examples is the barringer meteor crater near' b'winslow, arizona.' b'' b'asteroids are material left over from the formation of the' b'solar system. one theory suggests that they are the remains of a' b'planet that was destroyed in a massive collision long ago. more' b'likely, asteroids are material that never coalesced into a' b'planet. in fact, if the estimated total mass of all asteroids was' b'gathered into a single object, the object would be only about' b'1,500 kilometers miles) across less than half the' b'diameter of our moon.' b'' b'thousands of asteroids have been identified from earth. it' b'is estimated that are bright enough to eventually be' b'photographed through earth-based telescopes.' b'' b'much of our understanding about asteroids comes from' b'examining pieces of space debris that fall to the surface of' b'earth. asteroids that are on a collision course with earth are' b'called meteoroids. when a meteoroid strikes our atmosphere at' b'high velocity, friction causes this chunk of space matter to' b'incinerate in a streak of light known as a meteor. if the' b"meteoroid does not burn up comp