-water ocean. this ocean is covered' b'by an ice crust that has formed where water is exposed to the' b"cold of space. europa's core is made of rock that sank to its" b'center.' b'' b'like europa, the other two galilean moons ganymede and' b'callisto are worlds of ice and rock. ganymede is the largest' b'satellite in the solar system larger than the planets mercury' b'and pluto. the satellite is composed of about percent water or' b"ice and the rest rock. ganymede's surface has areas of different" b'brightness, indicating that, in the past, material oozed out of' b"the moon's interior and was deposited at various locations on the" b'surface.' b'' b'callisto, only slightly smaller than ganymede, has the' b'lowest density of any galilean satellite, suggesting that large' b'amounts of water are part of its composition. callisto is the' b'most heavily cratered object in the solar system; no activity' b'during its history has erased old craters except more impacts.' b'' b'detailed studies of all the galilean satellites will be' b'performed by the galileo orbiter.' b'' b'' b'saturn' b'' b'no planet in the solar system is adorned like saturn. its' b'exquisite ring system is unrivaled. like jupiter, saturn is' b'composed mostly of hydrogen. but in contrast to the vivid colors' b"and wild turbulence found in jovian clouds, saturn's atmosphere" b'has a more subtle, butterscotch hue, and its markings are muted' b"by high-altitude haze. given saturn's somewhat placid-looking" b'appearance, scientists were surprised at the high-velocity' b'equatorial jet stream that blows some kilometers b'miles) per hour.' b'' b'three american spacecraft have visited saturn. pioneer b'sped by the planet and its moon titan in september b'returning the first close-up images. voyager followed in' b'november sending back breathtaking photographs that' b"revealed for the first time the complexities of saturn's ring" b'system and moons. voyager flew by the planet and its moons in' b'august b'' b'the rings are composed of countless low-density particles' b"orbiting individually around saturn's equator at progressive" b'distances from the cloud tops. analysis of spacecraft radio waves' b'passing through the rings showed that the particles vary widely' b'in size, ranging from dust to house-sized boulders. the rings are' b'bright because they are mostly ice and frosted rock.' b'' b'the rings might have resulted when a moon or a passing body' b'ventured too close to saturn. the unlucky object would have been' b'torn apart by great tidal forces on its surface and in its' b'interior. or the object may not have been fully formed to begin' b"with and disintegrated under the influence of saturn's gravity. a" b'third possibility is that the object was shattered by collisions' b'with larger objects orbiting the planet.' b'' b'unable either to form into a moon or to drift away from each' b'other, individual ring particles appear to be held in place by' b'the gravitational pull of saturn and its satellites. these' b'complex gravitational interactions form the thousands of ringlets' b'that make up the major rings.' b'' b'radio emissions quite similar to the static heard on an am' b'car radio during an electrical storm were detected by the voyager' b'spacecraft. these emissions are typical of lightning but are' b"believed to be coming from saturn's ring system rather than its" b'atmosphere, where no lightning was observed. as they had at' b"jupiter, the voyagers saw a version of earth's auroras near" b"saturn's poles." b'' b'the voyagers discovered new moons and found several' b'satellites that share the same orbit. we learned that some moons' b"shepherd ring particles, maintaining saturn's rings and the gaps" b"in the rings. saturn's 18th moon was discovered in from" b'images taken by voyager in b'' b'voyager determined that titan has a nitrogen-based' b"atmosphere with methane and argon one more like earth's in" b'composition than the carbon dioxide atmospheres of mars and' b"venus. titan's surface temperature of degrees celsius b'degrees fahrenheit) implies that there might be water-ice islands' b'rising above oceans of ethane-methane liquid or sludge.' b"unfortunately, voyager's cameras could not penetrate the moon's" b'dense clouds.' b'' b'continuing photochemistry from solar radiation may be' b"converting titan's methane to ethane, acetylene and in" b'combination with nitrogen hydrogen cyanide. the latter' b'compound is a building block of amino acids. these conditions may' b'be similar to the atmospheric conditions of primeval earth' b"between three and four billion years ago. however, titan's" b'atmospheric temperature is believed to be too low to permit' b'progress beyond this stage of organic chemistry.' b'' b'the exploration of saturn will continue with the cassini' b'mission. the cassini spacecraft will orbit the planet and will' b'also deploy a probe called huygens, which will be dropped into' b"titan's atmosphere and fall to the surface. cassini will use the" b"probe as well as radar to peer through titan's clouds and will" b'spend years examining the saturnian system.' b'' b'' b'uranus' b'' b'in january four and a half years after visiting' b'saturn, voyager completed the first close-up survey of the' b'uranian system. the brief flyby revealed more information about' b'uranus and its retinue of icy moons than had been gleaned from' b"ground observations since the planet's discovery over two" b'centuries ago by the english astronomer william herschel.' b'' b'uranus, third largest of the planets, is an oddball of the' b'solar system. unlike the other planets (with the exception of' b'pluto), this giant lies tipped on its side with its north and' b'south poles alternately facing the sun during an 84-year swing' b"around the solar system. during voyager 2's flyby, the south pole" b'faced the sun. uranus might have been knocked over when an' b'earth-sized object collided with it early in the life of the' b'solar system.' b'' b"voyager found that uranus' magnetic field does not follow" b'the usual north-south axis found on the other planets. instead,' b"the field is tilted degrees and offset from the planet's" b'center, a phenomenon that on earth would be like having one' b'magnetic pole in new york city and the other in the city of' b'djakarta, on the island of java in indonesia.' b'' b"uranus' atmosphere consists mainly of hydrogen, with some b'percent helium and small amounts of ammonia, methane and water' b"vapor. the planet's blue color occurs because methane in its" b'atmosphere absorbs all other colors. wind speeds range up to b'kilometers miles) per hour, and temperatures near the cloud' b'tops average degrees celsius degrees fahrenheit).' b'' b"uranus' sunlit south pole is shrouded in a kind of" b'photochemical "smog" believed to be a combination of acetylene,' b'ethane and other sunlight-generated chemicals. surrounding the' b"planet's atmosphere and extending thousands of kilometers into" b'space is a mysterious ultraviolet sheen known as "electroglow."' b'' b"approximately kilometers miles) below uranus'" b'cloud tops, there is thought to be a scalding ocean of water and' b'dissolved ammonia some kilometers miles) deep.' b'beneath this ocean is an earth-sized core of heavier materials.' b'' b'voyager discovered new moons, kilometers b'miles) in diameter, orbiting uranus. the five previously known b'miranda, ariel, umbriel, titania and oberon range in size from' b'520 to kilometers to miles) across. representing' b'a geological showcase, these five moons are half-ice, half-rock' b'spheres that are cold and dark and show evidence of past' b'activity, including faulting and ice flows.' b'' b"the most remarkable of uranus' moons is miranda. its surface" b'features high cliffs as well as canyons, crater-pocked plains and' b'winding valleys. the sharp variations in terrain suggest that,' b'after the moon formed, it was smashed apart by a collision with' b'another body an event not un