hydrogen assumes the' b"electrical properties of a metal. earth's magnetic field, on the" b'other hand, is produced by its spinning metallic core and is only' b'slightly tilted and offset relative to its center.' b'' b"voyager also shed light on the mystery of neptune's rings." b'observations from earth indicated that there were arcs of' b'material in orbit around the giant planet. it was not clear how' b'neptune could have arcs and how these could be kept from' b'spreading out into even, unclumped rings. voyager detected' b'these arcs, but they were, in fact, part of thin, complete rings.' b'a number of small moons could explain the arcs, but such bodies' b'were not spotted.' b'' b'astronomers had identified the neptunian moons triton in' b'1846 and nereid in voyager found six more. one of the new' b'moons proteus is actually larger than nereid, but since' b"proteus orbits close to neptune, it was lost in the planet's" b'glare for observers on earth.' b'' b'triton circles neptune in a retrograde orbit in under six' b'days. tidal forces on triton are causing it to spiral slowly' b'towards the planet. in to million years (a short time in' b'astronomical terms), the moon will be so close that neptunian' b'gravity will tear it apart, forming a spectacular ring to' b"accompany the planet's modest current rings." b'' b"triton's landscape is as strange and unexpected as those of" b'io and miranda. the moon has more rock than its counterparts at' b"saturn and uranus. triton's mantle is probably composed of" b"water-ice, but the moon's crust is a thin veneer of nitrogen and" b'methane. the moon shows two dramatically different types of' b'terrain: the so-called "cantaloupe" terrain and a receding ice' b'cap.' b'' b'dark streaks appear on the ice cap. these streaks are the' b'fallout from geyser-like volcanic vents that shoot nitrogen gas' b'and dark, fine-grained particles to heights of to kilometers' b"(1 to miles). triton's thin atmosphere, only 1/70,000th as" b"thick as earth's, has winds that carry the dark particles and" b'deposit them as streaks on the ice cap the coldest surface yet' b'found in the solar system degrees celsius, degrees' b'fahrenheit). triton might be more like pluto than any other' b'object spacecraft have so far visited.' b'' b'' b'pluto' b'' b'pluto is the most distant of the planets, yet the' b'eccentricity of its orbit periodically carries it inside' b"neptune's orbit, where it has been since and where it will" b"remain until march pluto's orbit is also highly inclined b'tilted degrees to the orbital plane of the other planets.' b'' b'discovered in pluto appears to be little more than a' b"celestial snowball. the planet's diameter is calculated to be" b'approximately kilometers miles), only two-thirds the' b"size of our moon. ground-based observations indicate that pluto's" b'surface is covered with methane ice and that there is a thin' b'atmosphere that may freeze and fall to the surface as the planet' b"moves away from the sun. observations also show that pluto's spin" b'axis is tipped by degrees.' b'' b'the planet has one known satellite, charon, discovered in' b"1978. charon's surface composition is different from pluto's: the" b'moon appears to be covered with water-ice rather than methane' b'ice. its orbit is gravitationally locked with pluto, so both' b"bodies always keep the same hemisphere facing each other. pluto's" b"and charon's rotational period and charon's period of revolution" b'are all earth days.' b'' b'although no spacecraft have ever visited pluto, nasa is' b'currently exploring the possibility of such a mission.' b'' b'' b'comets' b'' b'the outermost members of the solar system occasionally pay a' b'visit to the inner planets. as asteroids are the rocky and' b'metallic remnants of the formation of the solar system, comets' b'are the icy debris from that dim beginning and can survive only' b'far from the sun. most comet nuclei reside in the oort cloud, a' b'loose swarm of objects in a halo beyond the planets and reaching' b'perhaps halfway to the nearest star.' b'' b'comet nuclei orbit in this frozen abyss until they are' b'gravitationally perturbed into new orbits that carry them close' b'to the sun. as a nucleus falls inside the orbits of the outer' b'planets, the volatile elements of which it is made gradually' b'warm; by the time the nucleus enters the region of the inner' b'planets, these volatile elements are boiling. the nucleus itself' b'is irregular and only a few miles across, and is made principally' b'of water-ice with methane and ammonia materials very similar' b'to those composing the moons of the giant planets.' b'' b'as these materials boil off of the nucleus, they form a coma' b'or cloud-like "head" that can measure tens of thousands of' b'kilometers across. the coma grows as the comet gets closer to the' b'sun. the stream of charged particles coming from the sun pushes' b'on this cloud, blowing it back like a flag in the wind and giving' b'rise to the comet\'s "tails." gases and ions are blown directly' b'back from the nucleus, but dust particles are pushed more slowly.' b'as the nucleus continues in its orbit, the dust particles are' b'left behind in a curved arc.' b'' b'both the gas and dust tails point away from the sun; in' b'effect, the comet chases its tails as it recedes from the sun.' b'the tails can reach million kilometers million miles) in' b'length, but the total amount of material contained in this' b'dramatic display would fit in an ordinary suitcase. comets b'from the latin cometa, meaning "long-haired" are essentially' b'dramatic light shows.' b'' b'some comets pass through the solar system only once, but' b'others have their orbits gravitationally modified by a close' b'encounter with one of the giant outer planets. these latter' b'visitors can enter closed elliptical orbits and repeatedly return' b'to the inner solar system.' b'' b"halley's comet is the most famous example of a relatively" b'short period comet, returning on an average of once every b"years and orbiting from beyond neptune to within venus' orbit." b'confirmed sightings of the comet go back to b.c. this regular' b'visitor to our solar system is named for sir edmond halley,' b"because he plotted the comet's orbit and predicted its return," b'based on earlier sightings and newtonian laws of motion. his name' b'became part of astronomical lore when, in the comet' b'returned on schedule. unfortunately, sir edmond did not live to' b'see it.' b'' b'a comet can be very prominent in the sky if it passes' b'comparatively close to earth. unfortunately, on its most recent' b"appearance, halley's comet passed no closer than million" b'kilometers million miles) from our world. the comet was' b'visible to the naked eye, especially for viewers in the southern' b'hemisphere, but it was not spectacular. comets have been so' b'bright, on rare occasions, that they were visible during daytime.' b'historically, comet sightings have been interpreted as bad omens' b'and have been artistically rendered as daggers in the sky.' b'' b'the comet rendezvous/asteroid flyby (craf) spacecraft will' b'become the first traveler to fly close to a comet nucleus and' b'remain in proximity to it as they both approach the sun. craf' b'will observe the nucleus as it becomes active in the growing' b'sunlight and begins to have its lighter elements boil off and' b'form a coma and tails. several spacecraft have flown by comets at' b"high speed; the first was nasa's international cometary explorer" b'in an armada of five spacecraft (two japanese, two soviet' b'and the giotto spacecraft from the european space agency) flew by' b"halley's comet in b'' b'' b'conclusion' b'' b'despite their efforts to peer across the vast distances of' b'space through an obscuring atmosphere, scientists of the past had' b'only one body they could study closely earth. but since b'spaceflight through the solar system has lifted the veil on our' b'neighbors in space.' b'' b'we have learned more about our solar system and its members' b'than anyone had in the previous thousands of years. our automated' b'spacecraft have traveled to the moon and to all the planets' b'beyond our world except pluto; they have observed moons as large' b'as small planets, flown by comets and sampled the solar' b'environment. astronomy books now include detailed pictures of' b'bodies that were only smudges in the largest telescopes for' b'generations. we are lucky to be alive now to see these strange' b'and beautiful places and objects.' b'' b'the knowledge gained from our journeys through the solar' b'system has redefined traditional earth sciences like geology and' b'meteorology and spawned an entirely new discipline called' b'comparative planetology. by studying the geology of planets,' b'moons, asteroids and comets, and comparing differences and' b'similarities, we are learning more about the origin and history' b'of these bodies and the solar system as a whole.' b'' b"we are also gaining insight into earth's complex weather" b'systems. by seeing how weather is shaped on other worlds and by' b"investigating the sun's activity and its influence throughout the" b'solar system, we can better understand climatic conditions and' b'processes on earth.' b'' b'we will continue to learn and benefit as our automated' b'spacecraft explore our neighborhood in space. one current mission' b'is mapping venus; others are flying between worlds and will reach' b'the sun and jupiter after complex trajectory adjustments. future' b'missions are planned for mars, saturn, a comet and the asteroid' b'belt.' b'' b'we can also look forward to the time when humans will once' b'again set foot on an alien world. although astronauts have not' b'been back to the moon since december plans are being' b'formulated for our return to the lunar landscape and for the' b'human exploration of mars and even the establishment of martian' b'outposts. one day, taking a holiday may mean spending a week at a' b'lunar base or a martian colony!' b'' b'- end b'' 